ntinues to shape our politics and societies. Bringing French and francophone Belgian films into dialogue with carefully selected theories, O’Shaughnessy develops insights and an analytical framework that will become important resources for other scholars of contemporary cinema. This book explores cinema's capacity to register mutations in subjectivity, the material grounds for identity construction and the machinic dimension of neoliberal subjection. It also probes its capacity to imagine alternative economies and identities and an exit from neoliberal labour. By developing fresh insights into political cinema, this book provides engages with cinema’s response to neoliberalism in crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009xIn motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszBelgium. 0aMotion pictureszFrance. 0aNeoliberalism. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078039040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147444864240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474448642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474448642/original  a978-3-11-078039-0  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK